KANO – The Vice President, Kano Chamber of Commerce, Industries, Mines and Agriculture, KACCIMA, Ambassador Usman H Darma has urged the Police and all other respondents in the leadership tussle to comply with the court order. A Federal High Court Order has restrained Kano state Government, the Police and three others from giving any effect in respect of the removal of the Kano Chamber of Commerce leadership and subsequent appointment of caretaker committee to steer the affairs of KACCIMA pending the hearing and determination of motion on notice. The Vice President, Darma lamented that police have barricaded the premises of Kano Chamber of Commerce despite the court order restraining all the defendants from giving any effect in respect of the dissolving KACCIMA Exco Members, by the Kano State Government. He explained that the Federal High Court Kano gave an order on 29th March 2022 compelling all parties to maintain status quo pending the hearing and determination of motion on notice in respect of the KACCIMA leadership. Darma however threatened to institute a contempt proceeding against Kano state Commissioner of Police and 4 other defendant, for refusing to comply with Court Injunction in the Chamber Leadership tussles. He explained that “You see we are law abiding citizens, when Kano State Government erroneously dissolved us we approached court and with our prayer.” Darma declared that “Kano State Government lacks power known to law to dissolved KACCIMA leadership for being the part that KACCIMA has been established over 100 years ago and it is private entity” he said When contacted Kano Command’s Spokesperson, SP Abdullahi Haruna Kiyawa to know the basis of their action despite the court order, he told reporters that police had taken over the premises after a security report that hoodlums will ransack the place today. POLL ” We’re are there to protect lives and property, based on a report that some underworld are planning attacks on the Chamber. When asked if police were served with the court order of Federal High Court, the Spokesman insist that police have been deployed at the premises to maintain law and order.